node.text:
We work with the world’s best independent testing facilities to reach both ECE and DOT safety standards for all ATLAS helmets. They test every imaginable variable to ensure sure that our helmets exceed the standards that you expect when considering a new helmet. 

The VIAS Institute starts with testing 50 ATLAS helmets, assessing impact points all over the shell to make sure that standards are met and that your helmet keeps you protected when you need it most. They test different angles of impact, shape of object impacting the helmet as well as various impact velocities. 

But this is just the beginning. Atlas helmets are submitted to VIAS for regular batch testing and conformity checks!

ATLAS helmets are shipped all over the world, to every imaginable climate. VIAS test our gear in the extreme conditions that you might face. Whether you’re riding through a blizzard or carving turns in the desert canyons, our helmets have been engineered to meet those safety standards, whatever the weather. 

The revolutionary Fidlock system that ships with every helmet is tested by the VIAS Institute to ensure that the safety standard for buckle retention is met, meaning you can be sure that your buckle will remain secure if under load during an accident. 

Ride with confidence, knowing that your ATLAS 3.0 is tried and tested by the best.

node.text: What's up guys. Matt Rees here. Co-founder of Ruroc. I wanted to put a message out to tell you about an incredible new mission of ours. @Enginehawk. Since we launched Atlas, we've found it hard to find motorcycle clothing that matches the level of design and performance of our helmets. We found that the gear we were forced to use was old school. It lacked great design, fit poorly, and the armor made it downright uncomfortable. And so we built a team. We recruited world class designers, and experts in engineering from the motorcycle industry. The result? motorcycle gear that looks better, fits better, and protects better. On April 27th, Enginehawk launches its first range of INSANE products. Follow the page for our new product releases over the next month and enjoy all the epic sh*t we've got to show you in the run up to the launch! #Ruroc #Enginehawk

To keep up with demand for Ruroc helmets, we’ve ditched the supply chains that big brands use and built our own factory. Every helmet that comes out of our new state of the art facility will be made faster, stronger and better quality than ever before, while ensuring the best working conditions for our staff.

The Ruroc factory is the next step in our mission to become the best helmet brand in the world. 💪

node.text:
Introducing the Atlas 3.0 Prime, a contemporary flat-grey with a high-gloss finish to create a stylish and understated silhouette, while saving lives in more ways than one. 💪

Riding gives us all a sense of purpose. A sense of freedom and clarity that is hard to find anywhere else, the stresses of your day, your week or even your life melting away when you flick down the visor and fire up your bike. Nothing matters before or after, just what’s around you on the road and where you are heading next.

At Ruroc, both riding and the community have changed our lives, and we want to give back. To say thank you for their continued incredible work, we are donating $10 for every ATLAS 3.0 Prime sold to selected mental health charities, who work tirelessly to help remind all of you that we can escape the dark clouds, together.

Order the ATLAS 3.0 Prime on September 9, 00:01 London Time

node.text:
IMPACT ABSORPTION TESTS

These are also known as drop tests and are used to simulate the impacts of a helmeted head during a motorcycle accident. A magnesium headform designed to weigh the same as a human head is placed in a helmet and dropped from a specified height. Different drop heights are used to produce different impact speeds depending on the particular test to be carried out. The helmets are impacted against a steel anvil. Each regulation has specific requirements for the different anvil types and shapes. The headforms are fitted with accelerometers which measure the deceleration of the helmet during an impact. The deceleration is measured in G. This is a measured representation of the energy transmitted to the head during the impact. The lower the value the better the performance of the helmet. UN ECE also uses HIC (Head Injury Criterion) as a measurement value during drop tests. This is a calculation of energy with respect to time and is used to measure the likelihood of a head injury arising from an impact. The lower the HIC value, the better the performance of the helmet in protecting the rider’s head.

ECE 22.05

275G
RUROC AVERAGE *
171G

ALLOWABLE LIMIT HIC

SAVING LIVES IS OUR MISSION

Before you pull your helmet out of it’s box, before you try it on, before you trust it with your life, your helmet has undergone extensive safety testing above and beyond the DOT & ECE 22.05 standards.

Meet the Penetration Test. It's required for DOT testing. It assesses the ability of the shell to resist penetration from sharp projections and projectiles as well assessing the stiffness of the shell. A failure occurs if the striker makes contact with the headform. As ATLAS has a lightweight Carbon Fibre shell we use aramid fibres in the shell lay-up to reinforce the shell and prevent penetration.

node.text:
TESTED FOR OBLIQUE IMPACTS

This is a new test introduced for Regulation 22.06 to assess the performance of the helmet when impacted against an oblique anvil. It is now widely regarded that rotational acceleration forces experienced from glancing blows are a significant contributor to serious brain injury. A helmeted headform is dropped at 8m/s using the same method as the linear drop test onto a 45° oblique anvil. Sandpaper is securely fixed to the top surface of the anvil. Impacts are performed on two different helmets on five impact positions. The performance of the helmet is assessed using PRA (Peak of the resultant rotational acceleration) and BrIC (Brain Injury Criterion). PRA is a measurement of rotational acceleration, the lower the value the better the performance. BrIC is calculated using angular rates of acceleration at a specified point of the impact, like HIC this is a calculation to predict the likelihood of a head injury from the impact. The lower the score the better the performance of the helmet in protecting the rider against injuries from glancing blows.

PRA LIMIT
10400 RAD/S2
RUROC AVERAGE *
3116 RAD/S2

BRIC LIMIT
0.78
RUROC AVERAGE *
0.32

*Oblique impact averages calculated from development tests at Newton Lab from tests conducted in 2021.
